Anonymous Sun 30 Aug 2020 00:31:26 No.32463562 Report
Quoted By:
>>32462742
With a novel you need to have more thoroughly designed characters, settings, and character arcs, and importantly, you need to be careful about how you distrubute that information to your readers. Readers are always wanting to know more, and your job as an author is to continually provide satisfying answers to your reader's unspoken questions while always establishing more questions for them to wonder about. If they run out of questions - learn all there is to know about a character or even just think that they have, for example - they lose interest. Answering interesting questions too quickly is wasteful, but taking too long or teasing answers too often can frustrate readers.

When I come up with a premise I like to write out rough outlines of the setting, plot, and important characters. For each outline I write out any questions I can think of. Why does character X have Y personality trait? How do these two species generally view one another? What would it take for this character to go against some deeply held belief? If a question and its answer are both interesting I try to work them into the story and if not then at least I have a better designed foundation to build on.
